nodes.title: Why Segments ?
widgets_values:
In certain situations, placing an object entirely within a single tile is essential for achieving consistent results. By applying a mask to an object, it can be sampled separately from the rest of the image. The masked area will then be upscaled to match the tile size, enhancing its detail.

This technique can also be used to repair or modify elements by applying different settings, prompts, or denoise values using the function.

After the entire image is processed, the segmented areas will be handled. ImpactPack is compatible with TBG ETUR segmentation entries, making it possible to automate the selection process.

nodes.title: Why pre Upscaling ?
widgets_values:
Begin the upscaling process by increasing the image size in gradual steps—such as doubling the megapixel count—so the sampler can incrementally add more detail at each stage. It’s often beneficial to first enhance the original image at its native resolution before proceeding with any upscaling.

Most upscaling tools, like SDUltimate, use an ESGAN upscaling step followed by standard interpolation downscaling before any further refinement, typically without providing previews of these intermediate stages.

I prefer to inspect the upscaled image before moving on to generative refinement, as this allows for early detection of artifacts or issues. In many cases, performing the initial upscale without a model produces a less defined result, giving the sampler greater flexibility to generate new, high-quality details

nodes.title: Why use Redux?
widgets_values:
Why use Redux?
Redux regenerates the image while preserving its overall composition and style.
A value of 1 means full reconstruction with strict adherence to the original
Lower values allow more creative freedom in the output
A value of 0 disables Redux entirely
If neither a Redux Clip nor a Style Model is connected, Redux will automatically be disabled
Redux is particularly useful for preserving fine materials, textures, and structural composition. In many cases, it can serve as a lightweight alternative to ControlNets.

nodes.title: ControlNets
widgets_values:
You can add as many ControlNets as you like.
currently, the only available preprocessors are Depth, Canny, Canny Edge, and None. We’ve excluded Pose because the subject will be divided into tiles, making pose estimation ineffective in this context.
A global ControlNet strength modifier is available to help fine-tune all ControlNets at once.
The ControlNet preprocessor works directly on each tile, allowing it to operate at the tile's full resolution. This differs from other refiners like Ultimate Upscale, where the ControlNet input is cropped, and a tile only uses a small portion of the full ControlNet resolution. With our setup, each tile benefits from full-resolution preprocessing.
